Energy efficiency Data Set¶

Abstract: This study looked into assessing the heating load and cooling load requirements of buildings (that is, energy efficiency) as a function of building parameters.

Source:

The dataset was created by Angeliki Xifara (angxifara'@'gmail.com, Civil/Structural Engineer) and was processed by Athanasios Tsanas (tsanasthanasis'@'gmail.com, Oxford Centre for Industrial and Applied Mathematics, University of Oxford, UK).

A. Tsanas, A. Xifara: 'Accurate quantitative estimation of energy performance of residential buildings using statistical machine learning tools', Energy and Buildings, Vol. 49, pp. 560-567, 2012

Attribute Information:

The dataset contains eight attributes (or features, denoted by X1..X8) and two responses denoted by y1 and y2. The aim is to use the eight features to predict each of the two responses.

  • X1 Relative Compactness
  • X2 Surface Area
  • X3 Wall Area
  • X4 Roof Area
  • X5 Overall Height
  • X6 Orientation
  • X7 Glazing Area
  • X8 Glazing Area Distribution
  • y1 Heating Load
  • y2 Cooling Load

Modeling¶

  1. Create features and target numpy arrays out of the dataframe. Since some Machine Learning Algorithms do not function properly with Pandas dataframes, it is advisable to get into the habit of using Numpy arrays
  2. Import relevent ML libraries
  3. Split the data into training and test sets
  4. Create pipelines to simplify multi-model fitting and evaluation
In [14]:
X = df[["Relative Compactness", "Surface Area", "Roof Area", 
        "Overall Height", "Wall Area", "Glazing Area"]].values

y = df[["Heating Load","Cooling Load"]].values

In [18]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error
In [19]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline, make_pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

Create 3 pipelines for the three different models under consideration: linear regression, polynomial regression, and random forest regression

In [20]:
ln_pipe = Pipeline([('scaler', StandardScaler()),('lin_reg', LinearRegression())])

pl_pipe = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree=2), LinearRegression(fit_intercept = False))

rf_pipe = Pipeline([('scaler', StandardScaler()),('rft_reg', RandomForestRegressor())])
In [21]:
pipelines = [ln_pipe, pl_pipe, rf_pipe]
pipe_dict = {0:"Linear Regressor", 1:"Polynomial Regressor", 2:"Random Forest Regressor"}

Model fitting and evaluation¶

  • Fit all models using a simple loop
  • Evaluate each model using a separate loop: obtain the model accuracy, mean absolute error, and the mean squared error
In [22]:
for pipe in pipelines:
    pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)
In [23]:
for i, pipe in enumerate(pipelines):
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, pipe.predict(X_test))
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, pipe.predict(X_test))

    print(f"{pipe_dict.get(i)} Accuracy: {pipe.score(X_test, y_test):.4f}")
    print(f"{pipe_dict.get(i)} MAE : {mae:.4f}")
    print(f"{pipe_dict.get(i)} MSE : {mse:.4f}\n")

Model Persistence¶

Save trained models so that they don't have to be retrained every time.

In [24]:
from joblib import dump, load

for i, model in  enumerate(pipelines):
    dump(model, f"{pipe_dict.get(i).replace(' ','_')}.joblib")
In [25]:
new_linear_reg = load('Linear_Regressor.joblib')
